Agency Name: Department of Health and Human Services
Investment Title: FDA OC User Fee and Financial Reporting Systems
Project Name: FDA OC User Fee System Enhancements
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: All major functions of UFFRS are available to users through its three production systems.  However, changes to respond to Legislative actions and/or regulations that require corresponding IT adjustments, technical upgrades, or internal business or administrative requirements from the FDA user community are frequent, and usually cannot be anticipated in advance.  The User Fee System contract for O&M supports such changes under individual IDEA Task Orders.  Most are Fixed Price and range from $.050M to $.500M.  Estimated funding for  Task Orders was identified as activities in the FY14 submission.  However, because of their type and limited size, and the inability to accurately project Task Order start dates, durations, or actual costs until awarded, HHS has recommended the User Fee system be managed as an O&M investment.  As a result of that change, only enhancements that require significant additional resources or pose major risks will be identified as projects.  No enhancements that meet those criteria are anticipated FY13 for FY14. All activities initiated with FY13 or FY14 funding will be reported until completion.

Agency Name: Department of Health and Human Services
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: In 2004, the Federal Health Architecture (FHA) Program was established as an OMB line of business (LoB) to support Federal activities related to the development and adoption of Health IT standards, ensuring that agencies seamlessly and securely exchange health data with other agencies, other government entities, and with other public and private organizations. In 2006, Executive Order 13410 required healthcare programs administered or sponsored by the Federal government to promote quality and efficient delivery through the use of health information technology. HHS was tasked with developing a program to assist agencies to meet EO 13410 and monitor their progress. Subsequently, the Office of the National Coordinator for Health Information Technology (ONC) was established.   The FHA is a partnership among Federal Agencies and the OMB, and managed by ONC with HHS, acting as the Managing Partner, along with the Department of Defense and the Department of Veterans Affairs, acting as Lead Partners, provides funding for the program. These agencies collaborate to advance health information interoperability between Federal Agencies, and between agencies and the tribal, state, local and private sectors.  Through the FHA program, Federal Agencies have joined together to rapidly and efficiently implement government-wide solutions for interoperable and secure health information exchange that address agency business priorities, while protecting citizen privacy. FHA serves the needs of more than 20 Federal Agencies in domains as diverse as military and veterans' healthcare, public health monitoring, long-term care and disability services, research, tribal health services and many other critical Federal priorities.
PM Experience Level: 4-Other certification with 4 or more years PM experience (within the last five years)

Agency Name: Department of Health and Human Services
Investment Title: HHS Unified Financial Management System (UFMS) Investment
Project Name: UFMS Release 12 (R12) Assessment and Upgrade Project
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: The UFMS investment consists of the operations and maintenance of the existing UFMS system and projects to enhance the UFMS system including Oracle R12 upgrade assessment and the R12 upgrade (implementation).  This investment is part of HHS' broader Financial System Improvement Program (FSIP) and supports its Goal 2: Maintain a Secure, Reliable and Efficient Systems Environment.  In addition it supports the objectives of the HHS Chief Financial Officer community and HHS strategic plan.  Oracle's E-Business Suite environment will become obsolete in December 2015 when Oracle's exception to the extended support ends.  At that point HHS will stop receiving quarterly patches for UFMS which may impact the security, reliability and availability of these systems and leave the system vulnerable.  The latest version of Oracle Federal Financials (R12) also provides significant functional enhancements that will strengthen HHS' compliance with Federal Financial Management Improvement Act (FFMIA).  HHS seeks to upgrade UFMS to version R12 in a managed federal cloud/hosting environment through this investment.

Agency Name: Department of Health and Human Services
Investment Title: IHS Resource and Patient Management System (RPMS) - Maintenance & Enhancements
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: Transitioning to the International Classification of Disease, 10th Revision (ICD-10) includes the design, programming, testing and implementation of the ASC X12 5010 and NCPDP D.0 transaction sets and the ICD-10 code sets within the Resource and Patient Management System (RPMS).  Design of this project will include the capability of running ICD-9 and ICD-10 in parallel. Strategic management and planning, extensive system changes, specialized education, and effective training and implementation are essential to a successful transition. The process will require the Office of Information Technology (OIT) to significantly modify the RPMS to accommodate the new codes. To this end, training of all staff that utilize ICD-10, including providers, billers, coders and others, will be required to ensure not only an efficient implementation of the code set conversion software, but also an understanding of the documentation requirements and coding guidelines.
Release Every Six Mo Comment: The characteristics of this project require a high degree of interdependency among 30+ application updates to fulfill the requirements set forth by the Centers for Medicare and Medicaid (CMS) mandate for ICD-10 implementation.  The requirements analysis, design, development, and testing of all application changes has been scheduled toward the ultimate goal of a single release date in order to meet the overall requirement of upgrading the entire RPMS system to use ICD-10 diagnosis codes for clinical documentation and billing. All modifications must be tested in an integrated environment and released to users at the same time.  Releasing application changes at earlier or more frequent intervals was not feasible for this project and would have adversely affected the production environments of users and impacted patient care as all modifications were dependent on one another to provide the necessary capabilities required by the mandate.

Agency Name: Department of Health and Human Services
Investment Title: NIH NCI Cancer Therapy Evaluation Program (CTEP)
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: The Cancer Therapy Evaluation Program Enterprise System (CTEP-ESYS) is the primary data collection mechanism for the Division of Cancer Treatment and Diagnosis' vast clinical trials program. CTEP-ESYS collects safety and clinical results data on 1,356 ongoing cancer clinical trials (trials not yet completed); of those 1,116 are treatment trials. CTEP-ESYS tracks more than 27,000 patients per year in more than 24 disease areas. The system supports 517,000 drug orders and 37,000 registered investigators. Data reporting and analysis in real time is critical to ensuring adequate monitoring of the ongoing clinical research. Timely data reporting and analysis also assures effective planning for the required successor studies, thus accelerating the evaluation of promising new agents and regimens for patients with cancer. An effective CTEP-ESYS allows investigators and researchers to focus on scientific opportunity, patient safety and reducing the burden of cancer on the public by finding better ways to treat, control and cure cancer. There are many components that support CTEP needs including protocol tracking, agent authorization and tracking, clinical data reporting, adverse event reporting and processing, clinical trials auditing, financial management, investigational new agent and development, disease management and tracking, annual report generation, regulatory activities, account management, investigator registration, reporting and analysis. CTEP-ESYS consist of a common repository that interfaces with suite of applications that are integrated and support the cancer-clinical trials infrastructure.

Agency Name: Department of Health and Human Services
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: In 2012, the Physician Quality Reporting System (PQRS) will continue to offer expanded measures and reporting options for Eligible Professionals (EPs).  The number of quality measures to be included for 2012 is not established at this time.  There were 190 quality measures in 2011.  For 2012 there will continue to be multiple reporting options through claims and will continue to include measure groups.  The Physician Quality Reporting System will support multiple submission methods such as Electronic Health Record Registry and Group Practices Reporting Options (GPROs I and II).  It is anticipated that the incentive will be based, as in past years, on the total allowed Medicare Physician Fee Schedule charges for the reporting period.Continuing in 2012, there will be the Electronic Prescribing (eRx) Initiative which is available for those EP's that are considered successful electronic prescribers (eRx-ers) as defined in the CMS eRx specifications.  As in 2011, both individual and selected GPROs may report on the eRx measure through claims, registries or EHR's.  Successful eRx-ers will potentially earn an incentive payment based on their total allowed Medicare Physician Fee Schedule charges for the 12 month reporting period.  Currently successful electronic prescribers will not be eligible to receive an incentive under the eRx Incentive Program if they are also receiving an incentive under the Health Information Technology (HIT) Incentive Program authorized by the Recovery Act, enacted on February 17, 2009. Future rule making may further align the incentives programs. EP's that are not electronic prescribers will receive a penalty adjustment starting in 2012 based on the first 6 months of claims data submitted in 2011.  The eRx Initiative will provide Interim Feedback Reporting to EP's.  Measures and other data sources may be added for the 2012 Program Year to allow EP's options for successfully reporting the eRx measure for both the penalty and incentive programs.EP's may have the flexibility of expanding and adding additional hardship codes for exemption for all years.
PM Experience Level: 4-Other certification with 4 or more years PM experience (within the last five years)

Agency Name: Department of Health and Human Services
Investment Title: CMS MACBIS (Medicaid & CHIP Business Information and Solutions)
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: Medicaid, authorized by Title XIX of the Social Security Act, and CHIP, reauthorized by the Children's Health Insurance Program Reauthorization Act of 2009 (CHIPRA) signed into law on February 4, 2009, play an important role in financing health care for approximately 48 million people throughout the country.  By 2014, it is expected that an additional 16 million people will become eligible for Medicaid and CHIP as a result of the Affordable Care Act (Public Law 111-148 - Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act). In order to implement the statute, CMS must provide for a mechanism to ensure timely approval of Medicaid and CHIP state plans, waivers and demonstrations and provide for a repository for all Medicaid and CHIP program that supplies data to populate  Healthcare.gov (sec. 1103) as well as other required reports. With these tremendous statutory changes in the Medicaid and CHIP programs, CMS will undergo a transformation from a reactive, mostly paper based processing entity to an active, electronic based program manager by automating and streamlining the current systems and processes.CMS is in the process of evaluating Medicaid systems currently operating, in order to build an enterprise architecture platform and data repository.  Ideally, CMS would allow for a single point of entry to access various program and operational data applications.  This effort will be implemented in phases over several years.  Phase 1 will provide for a Medicaid and CHIP Program data system (MACPro) accessed through a web portal/portlet that will automate the input and retrieval of data from the states related to the State Medicaid and CHIP Plans (including Demonstrations and Waivers).  This system will also support an efficient workflow for the review and approval of the State Medicaid and CHIP process. States will access this system and submit program information into structured data templates.  CMS staff will review the templates for compliance with federal statute, regulation and policy, provide feedback to the states and track/monitor the review and approval process.  Future project phasing will provide for the design, delivery and implementation of financial management programs and performance and quality metrics. CMS must meet a hard deadline for the implementation of the Affordable Care Act. This system will be operational in phases with the eligibility, benchmark plans, demonstrations and waivers portions/modules to be implemented before December 30, 2013.
PM Experience Level: 8-No certification, but with between 2 and 4 years PM experience (within the last five years)

Agency Name: Department of Health and Human Services
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: The Department of Health and Human Services (HHS) Trusted Internet Connections (TIC) Project was formed to comply with Office Management and Budget (OMB) Memorandum M-08-05, Implementation of Trusted Internet Connections.  The purpose of the TIC program is to optimize individual external connections, including Internet Points of Presence (PoP) currently in use by the federal government.  The TIC Initiative establishes a basis for consolidated infrastructure to achieve interoperability and communication among operating divisions.  In response to this initiative, HHS will adopt a network and security architecture that complies with the Department of Homeland Security (DHS) TIC requirements and reduces the total number of external connections to include Internet, inter-agency, partner, contractor, educational, health and research connectivity.   Once implemented, the TIC environment will improve HHS's incident response capability; reduce the number of external connection points within HHS; and provide centralized monitoring of HHS network security controls.  HHS TIC aligns with the HHS 2007-2012 Strategic Plan for IT infrastructure consolidation.  This strategy employs the sharing and reuse of common, standards-based materials and programs that support the business of computer technology.

Agency Name: Department of Health and Human Services
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: Interactions between medicine and industry have a wide spectrum of purposes and resulting impacts. Collaboration may promote discovery and development of new technologies that improve individual and public health. However, financial ties may create conflicts of interest in other aspects of medicine: clinical practice, clinical and basic science research, medical education, standard setting, and medical publications.Applicable manufacturers and group purchasing organizations (GPOs) must begin collection of all applicable transfers of value starting on August 1, 2013 and must report the data to CMS and attest to the data on an annual basis thereafter. After a formal data review and dispute process by the covered recipients and submission of corrections by the applicable manufacturers and GPOs, CMS must publish the data on a public website. Data must be published in a way that it is easy to use, is searchable, can be aggregated, and is downloadable.Manufacturers who produce any drugs, devices, biologicals, or medical supplies covered under Medicare, Medicaid, or the Children's Health Insurance Program (CHIP) are subject to Open Payments reporting requirements. Except in special circumstances outlined in the Final Rule, applicable manufacturers and GPOs must disclose and attest to all applicable transactions (payments, other transfers of value, investment interests, etc.) made to any covered recipients, regardless of whether the transfer of value was related to a covered product.CMS anticipates that patients, physicians, manufacturers, GPOs, third party commercial services, the press, academic researchers, other researchers, and the general public will utilize the data collected by this program.
PM Experience Level: 4-Other certification with 4 or more years PM experience (within the last five years)

Agency Name: Department of Health and Human Services
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: The purpose of this project is to collect, edit, and store encounter data submitted by Medicare Medicaid Plans (MMPs) and other entities' encounter data necessary to describe and price (Medicare only) a health care encounter along with any other activity as directed under the Capitated Financial Alignment Demonstration. Under the capitated model of the financial alignment demonstrations, the Medicare-Medicaid Coordination Office is working with participating States to test a new payment and service delivery model to improve the quality of care that individuals dually eligible for Medicare and Medicaid (Medicare-Medicaid enrollees) receive.  The goals are to expand access to seamless, integrated programs, while reducing expenditures under Medicare and Medicaid, and enhancing the quality of care furnished. This project modifies the existing Encounter Data System (EDS) for purposes of processing those encounter data described as being Medicare services to develop the capability to price the MMP health care encounter data to be able to estimate the cost of a dually eligible beneficiary enrolled in an MMP. For those encounter data described as being Medicaid services, the data is collected, edited at the translator level and stored along with the Medicare services encounter data in the CMS Repository. Under this project a copy of all encounter data submitted by the MMPs is also sent to the corresponding State Medicaid Agency. The project includes analysis, development, testing, implementation, and maintenance of the Medicare Medicaid Data System (MMDS), including modifications to EDS, as well as operational and policy training to MMPs and other entities. Inherent existing functionality of the EDS, such as identification of diagnoses codes to be sent to the Risk Adjustment Processing System (RAPS), processing and submitting Part D Events is included.Because the system is modified to receive Demonstration Medicaid Encounters as well, the capacity to process encounters submitted in the NCPDP format and Dental Encounters will be added.
PM Experience Level: 8-No certification, but with between 2 and 4 years PM experience (within the last five years)

Agency Name: Department of Health and Human Services
Investment Title: HHS Financial Business Intelligence System (FBIS) Investment
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: This project was originally reported under the HHS Modernization Program investment and Unified Financial Management System (UFMS). With the new direction of improving Financial Systems Environment, a decision was made to set up a Financial Business Intelligence System(FBIS) investment that covers the Business Intelligence effort. As a result of the decision, this project was moved to the FBIS investment. This project addresses the gap identified during the UFMS Deep Dive Assessment to improve reporting and decision support across HHS OpDivs and StaffDivs. The scope of this project is to (1) define an HHS-wide reporting strategy, (2) to implement Oracle's Business Intelligence Enterprise Edition (OBIEE) and, 3) address business needs in reporting. It creates an information-driven, collaborative financial management environment where stakeholders at all levels across the organization have access to timely and accurate information that measures performance, increases transparency, and enhances decision-making.

Investment Title: FEMA - Integrated Public Alert & Warning System (IPAWS)
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: EAS Primary Entry Point (PEP) Expansion program is a resilient capability for the President to alert and warn citizens in times of national crisis. It can also be used by local authorities to provide local life-saving information during a crisis. PEP stations are commercial radio stations with additional FEMA-supplied capabilities that allow stations to operate and broadcast alert and warning messages under all-hazards. The IPAWS Program is expanding the number of PEP radio stations to provide direct coverage to 90% of the U.S. population.  The PEP expansion installs FEMA equipment into an existing commercial radio station.

Investment Title: FEMA - Integrated Public Alert & Warning System (IPAWS)
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: IPAWS-OPEN is an application and data center infrastructure that provides alert aggregation, authentication, and dissemination to multiple communication media. Communication media includes radio via the EAS, cellular phones via the Commercial Mobile Alert System (CMAS), NOAA All Hazards Radio, TV, Internet, and social media services. This project provides updates to the system to increase capability and useability.

Investment Title: FEMA - Integrated Public Alert & Warning System (IPAWS)
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: The National Public Warning System (NPWS) Operations and Maintenance project of IPAWS provides the President with a resilient all-hazards capability to warn the American people in times of national crisis. The NPWS component consists of a federated system of systems consisting of FEMA warning message origination systems at multiple FEMA operations centers, Primary Entry Point (PEP) stations, and communications networks between the operations centers and the PEP Stations. The PEP Stations serve as national warning message entry points in to the  Emergency Alert System (EAS) which includes all other radio, TV, cable, wireline, and satellite network providers as defined in 47 CFR Part 11. The NPWS O&M project will provide annual and as needed operations and maintenance, including operating system upgrades, technology refreshes, and security patch implementation in addition to physical infrastructure maintenance.
Release Every Six Mo Comment: Not a software development project.

SIEM systems collect logs and other security-related documentation for analysis. Most SIEM systems work by deploying multiple collection agents in a hierarchical manner to gather security-related events from end-user devices, servers, network equipment -- and even specialized security equipment like firewalls, antivirus or intrusion prevention systems. The collectors forward events to a centralized management console, which performs inspections and flags anomalies.

Objectives / Expected Outcomes: Initial operating capabilities for pedestrian, outbound, and checkpoint.  This project includes the piloting of a re-engineered pedestrian process on 3 lanes at 1 pedestrian location (Paso Del Norte, TX).  In the outbound environment, Phase 1 will deploy one Tier 1 (robust, inbound-like) solution; five Tier 2 (fixed LPR+) solutions; and 36 Tier 3 (mobile capability) solutions.  Phase 1 also delivers LPR and VPC capabilities to Border Patrol checkpoints: a fixed solution at one checkpoint and tactical solutions and 14 checkpoints.  Finally, Phase 1 will deploy WHTI inbound technical solution to 10 remaining lanes at 4 locations.

Objectives / Expected Outcomes: Deployment A was an enhancement to current Cargo Release/Simplified Entry, Entry Summary, and Partner Government Agency (PGA) integration.
Deployment B was an enhancement to current Cargo Release/Simplified Entry, Entry Summary Validation (ESV), and PGA integration.

During this project capabilities will be created for Cargo Release/SE, Entry Summary,  Exports, Manifest, and technical platform. Cargo Release/SE will provide the single window for the international trade community with a more automated and modern process that streamlines data requirements, removes paper, and provides for expedited decisions by Federal agencies for imports. Entry Summary processing development focuses on critical system edits or checks that validate the accuracy of the data being submitted to CBP.  PGA Integration continues to build capabilities that allow previously unavailable data to be provided by ACE to PGAs for safety targeting on imports, increasing all agencies' ability to segment risk and focus on those shipments with security, health and safety, and admissibility concerns. Automated Export System re-engineering effort will incorporate current export processing features in ACE and create a single automated export processing platform for export manifest commodity, and export control and licensing transactions. Manifests will modernize Air and Manifest processing. The ability to integrate Air Manifest with SE and  Cargo Release to correlate manifest bills of lading with entries. The ability to integrate the ATS for screening and targeting Air In-Bond functionality. Truck, Sea, and Rail manifests have already been modernized.

The capabilities that will be created during this project are Cargo Release/SE, Entry Summary, Manifest, Exports, Accounts Management, PGA Integration, and Document Image System (DIS). Cargo Release/SE will provide the single window for the international trade community with a more automated and modern process that streamlines data requirements, removes paper, and provides for expedited decisions by Federal agencies for imports. Entry Summary processing development focuses on critical system edits or checks that validate the accuracy of the data being submitted to CBP.  Manifests will modernize Air and Manifest processing. The ability to integrate Air Manifest with Simplified Entry (SE) and  Cargo Release/Simplified Entry to correlate manifest bills of lading with entries. The ability to integrate the ATS for screening and targeting Air In-Bond functionality. Automated Export System re-engineering effort will incorporate current export processing features in ACE and create a single automated export processing platform for export manifest commodity, and export control and licensing transactions. PGA Integration continues to build capabilities that allow previously unavailable data to be provided by ACE to PGAs for safety targeting on imports, increasing all agencies' ability to segment risk and focus on those shipments with security, health and safety, and admissibility concerns.   Additional capabilities will be added to DIS. DIS gives the government the ability to request scanned images (or image files) from the Trade.

ACE Currently supports the processing of rail, sea, and truck electronic manifests.  Electronic manifests allow the government to more quickly determine if incoming cargo poses a risk or can proceed into the country. CBP will expand ACE to include air electronic manifests in 2015. This release also support the Mandatory use of ACE for all electronic cargo release and related entry summary filings. PGA integration for CPSC, FWS, TSA,FDA, APHIS, and FAS are scheduled for this release.

ACE is working closely with PGAs to implement Single Window, which is part of the International Trade Data System initiative.  Key Single Window capabilities will be deployed with this release (including ATF, IRS, BLS). Additional features include In-Bond processing and post release enhancements.
Mandatory use of ACE for all remaining portions of the CBP Cargo process is October 2016. This final planned release will include remaining PGA integration and additional system validations.
This Project includes the following O&M activites for the ACE Program: Hardware Maintenance, Infrastructure Support, Software Maintanence, and Code Refactoring and Maintanence.

VIS O & M Release 10.0. Replicate all data used for VIS ad-hoc reporting to a server, Deploy a VIS Web Services Extended interface for CRM, Enable VIS and CRM to exchange data, Add self-help screens to guide E-Verify user to re-set their password, retrieve their user ID or unlock their account.

VIS O & M Release 11.0. ELIS (C3) -VIS users will be able to query both C3 and ELIS systems to find the best sponsorship information for an applicant on first step rather than requiring the submission of a G-845 and/or G-845 supplement. PDF Generation Service (PGS) - VIS users will be able to replace functionality to convert the Memorandums of Understanding (MOUs) from MS Word to PDF and deprecate the Documentum Transformation Server (DTS). Extend ISRS for EAD - SAVE WEB-3 users will be able to provide ISRS (image) responses to agencies using I-766 documents (in addition to I-551 documents) and will be able to decrease IAV responses in SAVE and reduce second and third step queries. ELIS (International Addresses) - SAVE WEB-3 users will be able to return international sponsor addresses for sponsors on initial verification queries, be able to reduce the number of second and third steps required to return these addresses, and will be able to enable the data to be properly returned on second and third step when necessary.

VIS O & M Release 12.0. NARA - VIS System Owners will be able to implement a process and tools to delete VIS records that meet the criteria that have been inactive for at least ten years. Removal Order (E-Verify) - E-Verify users will be able to enhance the processing to access DOJ data related to removal order proceedings, will be able to have applicants evaluated against IJ decisions in their EOIR record so that applicants subject to a removal order will not receive a positive response, and will be able to enhance SVS and In-Application Reports to display removal order information for cases.

VIS O & M Release 13.0. CRM INTEGRATION-PHASE 1 VIS to CRM: To enable the AVANT CRM tool to use the most up-to-date Employer and Agency data, VIS will enable services to AVANT to alert it to changes to the VIS Database in real-time.

Technical Architecture Re-engineering - Verification components will be re-engineered into a service-based application architecture that enables system enhancement with new functionalities quickly and efficiently.  This will be accomplished by replacing the tightly coupled elements of the baseline architecture with standardized components and greater functional modularity. Key software components will be implemented using DHS cloud services to the maximum extent, selected for commonality with other USCIS systems, and with a preference for DHS cloud offerings over other possible approaches within USCIS.

The ACRIMe Modernization project is replacing the legacy ACRIMe system with an enterprise-based system, providing access regardless of the users' physical location. ACRIMe Modernization is automating numerous manual processes and providing web-based screens for ICE Agents to access the data used by LESC LESs in making status determinations, rather than having to re-process a subject's criminal and immigration history (as done with the legacy system).

The Status Determination Support project provides modules of functionality to ACRIMe that streamline the processes LESs use to manage ICE issued warrants and lookouts within the FBI's National Crime Information Center (NCIC) and to automate the searching of other systems.

The Automated Threat Prioritization (ATP) project is deploying a web-service that ACRIMe and other systems can call to perform an analysis of a subject's criminal and immigration history. The analysis returns a criminal offense level and a threat to community score that can be used by the calling system to automatically prioritize high-threat subjects.

The Alien Criminal History Entry Screen (ACES) allows ICE agents to enter a subject's information into the Enforcement Integrated Database, returning past criminal history information for the agent to analyze.
The Automated Threat Prioritization Maintenance project provides O&M support for the Automated Threat Prioritization system.

The CAII System Enhancements project will provide additional enhancements and functionality for the various CAII components. These include enhancing the NCIC Wants and Warrants Processing component with a new Warrant and Lookout request entry screen, and expanding the full search capability to ICE Agents so they can search DHS and FBI systems from a single integrated screen.

Agency Name: Department of Housing and Urban Development
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: The New Core Program is a multi-phase effort to modernize HUD's core financial and key administrative systems by transitioning the system functions to a shared services environment. New Core's first phase will migrate financial management and administrative functions to the Department of Treasury, Bureau of Fiscal Services, Administrative Resource Center's (ARC) shared services platform through multiple releases. Release 1 will allow HUD to migrate from the current e-Gov Travel Service 1 contract provider, FedTraveler, to the e-Gov Travel Service 2 contractor provider, Concur Government Edition, utilizing ARC for travel service administration.  This transition is required to meet Federal GSA e-Travel Service 2 requirements. Additionally, HUD will migrate to ARC's MoveLinq will allow HUD to retire contracts for HUD operated MoveLinq in late FY 2015.  This will also include migration to ARC's Oracle Federal Financials for travel and relocation accounting.
Release Every Six Mo Comment: The New Core Project is being broken out into smaller projects which represent three currently planned releases.
PM Experience Level: 4-Other certification with 4 or more years PM experience (within the last five years)

Agency Name: Department of Housing and Urban Development
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: Release 2 will allow HUD to migrate from HUD's Web Time and Attendance System to  an ARC managed, integrated time and attendance system that supports payroll processing. Implementation of ARC's WebTA will provide the framework to implement Managerial Cost Accounting, providing detailed cost information to aid daily management decisions.
Release Every Six Mo Comment: The New Core Project is being broken out into smaller projects which represent three currently planned releases.
PM Experience Level: 4-Other certification with 4 or more years PM experience (within the last five years)

Agency Name: Department of Housing and Urban Development
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: Release 3 will transfer functionality associated with budgeting, accounting, financial management, Federal reporting, and procurement to ARC managed Oracle Federal Financials system and PRISM system. This will provide HUD with an integrated core financial system intended to increase accuracy, speed, transparency, and accountability in financial management and budgeting for the agency, allow HUD to quickly accommodate legislative changes in its financial system, and make high-quality data available to support managerial decision-making to deliver HUD's mission.
Release Every Six Mo Comment: The New Core Project is being broken out into smaller projects which represent three currently planned releases.
PM Experience Level: 4-Other certification with 4 or more years PM experience (within the last five years)

Objectives / Expected Outcomes: Enable JSOC, DOJ components, and bureaus to conduct automated, advanced and dynamic analytics of cyber activity to determine if malware exists.  These next generation tools do not use static signature defined anti-virus which is ineffective against current threats.  Solution will be able to block malware that is found from executing on live DOJ networks.  DOJ requires a dedicated suite of capabilities to identify, prevent, and if necessary hunt, pursue, and mitigate Advanced Persistent Threats (APTs) that target DOJ networks.  These are high end threats that current capabilities (A/V, configuration, etc.) do not catch.  Currently DOJ can not inspect over 40% of network traffic because it is encrypted through SSL from host inside DOJ networks to destination; exactly where APT's operate.  Likewise, when APT are successful, DOJ can only maintain 5 days of PCAP information to rebuild network sessions and analyze the attack.  30-60 days is the industry standard to allow for notification and proper investigation of the malicious activity.  Implementing solutions will help position DOJ security services and defend the Department's networks and data.
Release Every Six Mo Comment: This is an integration project, not a software development project so a production release construct is not applicable.  Project will use traditional project management milestones.
PM Experience Level: 7-No certification, but with 4 or more years PM experience (within the last five years)

Release Every Six Mo Comment: The IPP Estimation project modernizes and enhances the data processing sub-systems needed to generate IPP index estimates. The new sub-system will use a completely new IPS database structure consisting of over 150 database tables. The new sub-system will also need to exchange data with existing legacy sub-systems which also consist of over 150 database tables. IPS needs to develop special software to support the transfer and sharing of data between the new IPS database and legacy databases. The cost of developing, testing, and deploying temporary versions of bridge software could rival the cost of the Index Estimation project, if these bridge changes happen too frequently. This would delay the eventual completion of the intended project as resources would be diverted to making frequent temporary changes to bridge software rather than providing modernized and enhanced software.

It will modernize and enhance the data processing subsystems needed to initiate new sample members for both IPP and PPI. The new subsystem will use a completely new IPS database structure consisting of over 200 database tables. It will also need to exchange data with existing legacy IPP and PPI subsystems which are supported by databases with a combined total of over 300 database tables. IPS needs to develop special software to support the transfer and sharing of data between the new IPS database and legacy databases. The cost of developing, testing, and deploying temporary versions of bridge software could rival the cost of the IPP Initiation project if these bridge changes happen too frequently. This would delay the eventual completion of the intended project as resources would be diverted to making frequent temporary changes to bridge software rather than providing modernized and enhanced software.

Investment Title: Messaging Services, Email and Remote Connectivity
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: The ClassNet Desktop Services Modernization Project (referred to as ClassNet Modernization) is a Global Information Technology Modernization (GITM) sponsored project focusing on building, testing and deploying upgrades to the ClassNet terminal servers overseas, and ClassNet thin clients world-wide.  This project implement and deploy updates to the ClassNet Citrix servers overseas, overseas fat clients, and thin clients world-wide to align the ClassNet system with objectives identified in the DoS IT Strategic Plan (ITSP) for fiscal years 2011-2013.  It is (1) Building, testing and making available Windows Embedded Standard (WES) 7, WES 2009 and HP Zero Client operating system images to 6700 overseas and 6000 domestic thin clients currently using embedded XP (XPe) operating system (XPe reaches End-of-Life in January 12, 2016), (2) Updating physical terminal servers from Windows 2003 to the Windows 2008R2 operating system,  and upgrading server memory and drives, (3) Installing Citrix XenApp 6.5 on terminal servers to support enhanced client monitoring and port security, (4) Integrating the latest PKI hardware and software, (5) Standardizing the baseline image installed on physical and virtual terminal servers (establishing an SOE-S), (6) Standardizing the baseline image presented to all ClassNet end users, (7) Ensuring system assets are under centralized management and configuration control, (8) Designing the system to meet short-term and long-term resource requirements, and (9) Upgrading the overseas fat clients running on the XP OS to the Microsoft Windows 7 image.

Investment Title: Messaging Services, Email and Remote Connectivity
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: The Citrix XenMobile Mobile Device Management solution allows for the comprehensive management of Government Furnished Equipment (GFE) mobile devices, apps and data.  It provides users access to approved mobile applications from a unified corporate apps store, including seamlessly-integrated email, browser, data sharing and supported apps.  IRM maintains control over mobile devices with full configuration, security, provisioning and support capabilities, ensuring compliance and control requirements while providing users with the freedom of a mobile device.  It will also serve as a launch bed to expand support of Department mobile applications on a secure platform. Leveraging the XenMobile platform on non-BlackBerry devices expands the Department's portfolio and limits its risk exposure to any potential business downgrade from BlackBerry.  Should that business falter, the Department would have a readily available alternate solution that will have been vetted and tested in the field. Introducing new mobile devices to start from Apple and then adding Android and Windows devices.

Objectives / Expected Outcomes: Program Engineering Support includes the GIISST and the ABC Study. The GNSS Intentional Interference and Spoofing Study Team (GIISST) was established by the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) Satellite Navigation Program Office and Aircraft Certification Service - Avionic Systems Branch (co-sponsors) to study existing threat assessments, relevant studies and data, and develop specific, actionable recommendations for the FAA with regard to technical, political/legal, and operational mitigations for civil aviation GNSS vulnerabilities to intentional interference and spoofing.  The Adjacent Band Capability (ABC) activity is a direct outgrowth of the Light Squared interference analysis. The first phase of the ABC effort is to investigate current susceptibility of aviation equipment to base station and handset LTE signals.

Objectives / Expected Outcomes: The ASKME Seg2 IDE will replace the four major, independent systems that were originally planned for Segment 2 (Budget Management (BMGMT), Airworthiness Directives Development (ADD), Airworthiness Certification (AC), and Compliance & Enforcement Actions (CEA)). This change in implementation strategy is the result of lessons learned from Segment 1, the recognition of higher risk related to integration of disparate systems, and the identification of a number of common requirements among the systems. The four independent projects have either been stopped or will be stopped before the end of FY14. The Seg2 IDE will first consolidate all of the requirements into a single requirements set, produce a high-level architecture and design, and produce a plan for the development, test, and implementation of the system within existing baseline constraints. The Seg2 IDE replanning process started on 7/2/2014, the consolidated detailed requirements document was signed 4/29/2015, and the JRC approved the replan on 6/17/2015. The deadline to complete the entire system (based on the existing baseline for the four disparate systems) is 9/29/2017.
Release Every Six Mo Comment: The initial part of the project (requirements consolidation, architecture, and design) will follow a waterfall pattern. Once these initial phases are complete, the program will assess whether a more iterative release plan will provide utility to the end-user community, increase user acceptance, etc. The Seg2 IDE replanning process started on 7/2/2014, the consolidated detailed requirements document was signed 4/29/2015, and the JRC approved the replan on 6/17/2015. The deadline to complete the entire system (based on the existing baseline for the four disparate systems) is 9/29/2017.

The DMIS/TROR application is capturing information related to each Federal agency's debt portfolio. It provides a management view of the Federal government's outstanding debt status. The Department of the Treasury uses DMIS/TROR to compile Federal debt collection figures and identify courses of action agencies must take to improve their compliance with the Debt Collection Improvement Act of 1996 (DCIA). Since DMIS/TROR acts as a central repository for DCIA information. It allows the Department of the Treasury a means of measuring compliance and preparing the Debt Collection Annual Report to Congress.

2015 Process and Technology Improvements (PTI) includes major and significant enhancments to FedDebt, Treasury Offset Program and Data Information Repository, all which are Debt Management Services specific applications. These enhancments are expected to improve the Bureau of the Fiscal Service's process in collecting and resolving delinquent debts owed to governmnet agencies.

The Debt Management Information System/Treasury Report On Receivables (DMIS/TROR) application is capturing information related to each Federal agency's debt portfolio. It provides a management view of the Federal governement's outstanding debt status. The Departmenet of the Treausry uses DMIS/TROR to compile Federal debt collection figures and identify courses of action agencies must take to improve their compliance with the Debt Collection Improvement Act of 1996 (DCIA). Since DMIS/TROR acts as a central repository for DCIA information, it allows the Department of the Treausry a means of measuring compliance and preparing the Debt Collection Annual report to Congress.

Objectives / Expected Outcomes: HR Connect is the core human resource system of the HR Connect Program Office (HRCPO), a shared services center HR service provider within the U.S. Department of Treasury.  The HR Connect application is the foundation of HRCPO's comprehensive suite of solutions and is rapidly becoming the gold standard among federal HR Line of Business (LOB) providers.HR practitioners, managers and employees use HR Connect (HRC) to perform a wide array of transactions at various stages of an employee's life cycle. HR practitioners use HR Connect to manage human capital and better utilize organizational data for strategic decision making. The system's paperless personnel actions electronically route actions for approval, greatly reducing processing time and the human error associated with manual processing.  Using one of the self-service components of Treasury SSC such as InService, managers can produce recruitment requests as well as requests for personnel actions, such as to promote and award employees.  Managers can also view reports and conduct a range of other  to build, sustain, and manage their team. Employees can make changes to their personal information, view information about their job and benefits, and report their time. As a result, HR practitioners, managers, and employees are partially relieved of cumbersome paperwork and are better able to participate in supporting their agencies' strategic objectives.  The U.S. Department of Commerce is in the process of consolidating its HR service centers by modeling its business processes within HR Connect and migrating HR data from its seven internal HR servicing bureaus into HR Connect.  They, along with our many other customers, recognize that, in addition to saving time and reducing cost, HR practitioners will be able to spend more time on strategic activities that help meet their agencies' core objectives.  HRCPO systems' robust security ensures the confidentiality, integrity and availability of customer data.  Aside from the core HR connect product, the Department of Commerce will also be leveraging our Workforce Analytics product, with plans to integrate EODS in the near future.
PM Experience Level: 4-Other certification with 4 or more years PM experience (within the last five years)

Taxpayers can view, print and download these documents in a PDF through IRS website. Using this web application, taxpayers can request their Return, Record of Account, Account, and Proof of Non-Filing transcripts for a four year period.  In addition, using this web interface, taxpayers can request Wage & Income documents for the last ten years.

Combine the IRS legacy Personal Identification Number (PIN) solutions for individual taxpayer filing (IMF) into a consolidated solution for 2014 and future years.  The eventual goal is to have one PIN for individual taxpayers in 2015 and beyond to facilitate electronic tax return filing (e-File) and to protect tax payer accounts against identity theft.The aim of this solution is to drive taxpayers to get a legacy Identity Protection (IP) PIN (proposed new name Taxpayer Filing Authentication Certificate [TFAC]) to protect their accounts and to facilitate e-Filing.  In order to receive a TFAC a taxpayer would have authenticate using the IRS e-Authentication (e-Auth) solution that leverage third-party out-of-wallet (OOW) data.  The legacy e-File PIN (EFP) would only be issued to taxpayers that cannot authentication with e-Auth (but can authenticate with legacy methods) to e-File.  Taxpayers issued a legacy e-File PIN would be subject to additional filters and reviews when they file their tax returns.

Project Name: Integrated Data Retrieval System (IDRS) - Filing Season 2012
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: Development for legislatively mandated tax law changes (for example, portions of Health Care and Education Reconciliation Act) and customer requested modernization and enhancement (for example, accelerate processing cycle)  * The Integrated Data Retrieval System (IDRS) is an IRS mission critical system consisting of databases and subsystems supporting IRS employees working active tax cases. It manages data retrieved from the Tax Master Files allowing IRS employees to take specific actions on taxpayer account issues, track status and post updates back to the Master Files. It provides for systemic review of case status, alleviating staffing needs and providing consistency in case control. Actions taken via IDRS include notice issuance, installment agreement processing, offers in compromise, adjustment processing, penalty and interest computations and explanations, credit and debit transfers within an account or other related accounts and research of taxpayer accounts for problem resolution of taxpayer inquiries.

Objectives / Expected Outcomes: Straight through Processing (STP) is a Treasury mandate to provide immediate recording of transactions and near real-time information for reconciliation and management of the Treasury's General Account (TGA) structure. The OTCnet STP implementation will be in two different segments due to immediate and long-term needs. The first implementation of STP in near term will require processing the appropriate Treasury RTNs for checks and deposit processing, processing a new Treasury RTN for Non-Appropriated Funds (NAF), voucher date change and sending it to Collections Information Repository (CIR).  The implementation will be closely coordinated with the Debit Gateway and CIR.  For commercial deposits, a new Treasury RTN will be defined for cash concentration and processed through CIR to Treasury Cash Management System (TCMS). The second implementation of STP will include processing of Adjustment/Correction and Rescinds (ACRs) for checks,, using XML 4.6 schema as standard interface and processing the of end-of-day file from Debit Gateway.
Release Every Six Mo Comment: Currently OTCnet does not have a production release scheduled every six months. However, the OTCnet team is in the planning phase to implement a release schedule, which will include a production release every six months.
PM Experience Level: 5-Other certification with between 2 and 4 years PM experience (within the last five years)

Objectives / Expected Outcomes: The Archive and Architecture Phase 1 will introduce a check transactional data archival process to improve OTCnet application performance and adhere to Fiscal Service' Data Retention Requirements.  Architecture Phase 1 will include breaking up operational  Online Transaction Processing (OLTP) database and the Archive database into two databases and defining an archive process.  The operational database will hold 18 months of current financial transactions and the archive database containing all historical information.  A new archive process will be defined to move data from operational database to the archive database. Modifications will be made for check search functionality and reports .  Additional architectural changes include converting batch jobs from Hibernate to Spring Batch framework. During phase 1, the archiving process will be limited to check processing only.  Archiving Phase 2 will include expanding archiving to deposit processing and adding additional reports from archive data.  Also, Hibernate optimization will be completed to move away from JBPM and use Spring Batch Framework where inefficiencies exist.
Release Every Six Mo Comment: Currently OTCnet does not have a production release scheduled every six months. However, the OTCnet team is in the planning phase to implement a release schedule, which will include a production release every six months.
PM Experience Level: 5-Other certification with between 2 and 4 years PM experience (within the last five years)

A system rewrite of TAAPS will begin in October 2011 with the first phase being define and documentation.  The rewrite may improve auction screens, reports, interfaces, or infrastructure to provide timely, accurate, and informative qualitative/quantitative analysis of Treasury Auctions.  Phase two will be the development phase and move towards the implementation process of the rewrite. Planned implementation of 9/30/2013.

In 2011, Treasury conducted 269 marketable security auctions to borrow the monies needed to fund the United States Government. The auction process must work flawlessly, remain absolutely secure, and operate without service disruptions which could erode public confidence and increase taxpayer costs for debt service. The Treasury Automated Auction Processing System (TAAPS) application and infrastructure have been in production for four years and in development for two years prior to that. In order to stay current with changes in technology, it is prudent to examine various components of the auction process to analyze the validity and adequacy of the utilized technology, application and infrastructure.  The business process components being analyzed have been organized into 8 areas of focus:1. Infrastructure & Security2. Credential Management3. Operational Efficiencies4. Internal Staff Recommendations5. External Participant Feedback6. Data Analytics7. Customer Relationship Management8. Institutional Website Revamp.

FIT recently completed a blueprint for financial management shared services.  The blueprint recommends a shared service approach whereby all Federal agencies migrate to one of several designated Federal and private financial management shared service providers (SSP) that offer, at a minimum, a common set of financial management services and products.  Further, the approach includes a lifecycle approval step where FIT reviews and compares an agency's migration proposal to the common services and products to verify the following:  (1) the agency's needs align with the common services and products; (2) the agency can offer support (e.g., regulatory, statutory) for any needs beyond the common services and products; and (3) any verified Services and Products gaps can be satisfied by one of the designated SSPs.  Once an agency has an acceptable modernization plan, it will begin a brief discovery phase with an SSP process whereby both organizations must agree that the services and products offered by the SSP satisfy the needs of the agency.

FIT has developed a series of financial management measures (e.g., price per invoice, on-time payments, discounts and interest paid) to capture the price and performance of a number of financial management processes (e.g., procure-to-pay, bill-to-collect) provided by Federal SSPs.  FIT captures and aggregates the measures reported by the SSPs in a reporting tool (or benchmarking tool) that aggregates the information as a government-wide benchmark.  FIT, Federal SSPs, and Federal agencies can use the benchmarking tool to compare the cost and performance of the Federal agencies financial management activities to the price and performance of the Federal SSPs.  The benchmarking tool is a web-based application with defined metrics based on seven financial management end-to-end business processes, including Procure-to-Pay and Bill-to-Collect.  The metrics are based on the price and performance of the aligned business processes of the Federal SSPs.  Examples of the metrics include price per invoice, statement of differences, on- time payments, discounts and interest paid.

Objectives / Expected Outcomes: The Veterans' Mental Health And Other Care Improvements Act Of 2008, Section 403, Public Law 110-387 mandates that the Department of Veterans Affairs (VA) conduct a pilot program over three years for contract care of eligible Veterans in selected Veterans Integrated Service Networks (VISNs). In response to this mandate, The Office of Policy Analysis within the Office of the Assistant Deputy Under Secretary for Health for Policy and Planning (ADUSH/PP), which is responsible for implementing this pilot, established a New Service Request(NSR)entitled Project Access Received Closer to Home (ARCH) Automated Eligibility Determination. A Business Requirements Document describing the business case and desired functionality for this NSR was signed by business owners on December 1, 2010. The Enhancing Veteran Experience and Access to Healthcare (EVEAH) Operating Plan for Fiscal Year (FY) 11-13 reflects this mandate and further supports action on the NSR. IT Patient Safety also evaluated this request and suggested that it be considered mandatory. The pilot program is scheduled for implementation between the second and third quarters of FY11.

Investment Title: Benefits 21st Century Paperless Delivery of Veterans Benefits
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: In FY11, using agile development methodology, the Veterans Benefits Management System (VBMS) created a software product that would improve efficiency in the Veterans claims management process. Phase 1 delivered a prototype to prove the concept of smart scanning, an electronic folder of images to replace the paper folder and web services application to establish a claim in the system. In Phase 2, the application will be changed from a prototype to an enterprise-capable application with the necessary supporting infrastructure to provide the foundational components for a nationally deployed paperless solution. VBMS is a business transformation initiative designed to reduce the processing time of a Veteran claim to 125 days. VBMS will increase efficiency, improve quality, reduce the backlog of pending claims, and ensure the timely and accurate delivery of disability benefits paid each month to Veterans and their beneficiaries.

Investment Title: Benefits 21st Century Paperless Delivery of Veterans Benefits

National deployment will integrate new and improved business processes through a software solution that is Web based and has the functionality to establish a claim and the paperless folder in VBMS. National Deployment will take place in phases throughout calendar year 2012 and 2013 to support and fulfill goal of an improved business process. VBMS is a business transformation initiative designed to reduce the processing time of a Veteran claim to 125 days from the current level of 161 days. VBMS will increase efficiency, improve quality, reduce the backlog of pending claims, and ensure the timely and accurate delivery of disability benefits paid each month to Veterans and their beneficiaries.

The Agent Orange (Fast Track) FY10 requestwas used to fund contractor support to design and develop an automated claims system called Fast Track for processing newly added Agent Orange (AO) Presumptive conditions, as well as any other new AO Presumptive conditions that may be added during the life of the contract using an Agile development methodology. The contractor has developed a suite of web-enabled claims forms that allows claimants to electronically download and, at the claimants option, electronically submit complete claims for Vietnam era service connection. Also for the first time in VA, the claimant and their provider(s) are now able to upload supporting medical evidence for the presumptive conditions in the form of Disability Benefits Questionnaires (DBQs) that become a part of the electronic claim. The initial development effort was funded out of the VA Innovations Initiatives (VAi2), and the FY11 and FY12 enhancement work is funded out of OI&T/Product Development as part of the President's budget.

CWINRS utilizes the Veterans Benefits Administrations (VBAs) Corporate database to maintain participant information and interfaces with VBAs BDN and VA Financial Management System (FMS) to process payment and accounting transactions.The project is to remove the CWINRS Application dependency on the legacy VBA BDN and use the newer Financial Accounting System for payment and accounting processing.

Project Name: St Paul Rules Based Claims Processing Pilot
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: The project is aligned with VAs overall goal to reduce backlog. The Rules-based Processing System (RBPS) is expected to reduce the processing time and eliminate decision variance by building the processing rules and guidance into the automated business rule system. Also, the project decreases the claims backlog and frees staff processing hours which can then be realigned to claims requiring manual intervention.

The Rules Based Processing System (RBPS) initiative will enhance rules-based processing of identified dependency claims, including award creation, denials, removals, automatic payment adjustments and letter generation. This System was piloted at the St. Paul Regional office. Approximately 30% of claims met the criteria for automatic processing. Of these claims, RBPS dramatically improved the processing times going from an average of 150 days to 5 days. This Project expects to increase this to 50% of claims being automatically processed.

VETSNET Release 13 will be application changes required to support the final conversion of Compensation and Pension records from the Benefits Delivery Network to the Veterans Benefit Administration Corporate Database. The primary objective for the SEP 2012 release is to allow for an October conversion of remaining BDN data. VETSNET will also expand support of Vocational Rehabilitation Benefits (CH31) and provide enhancements for Personal Funds of Patients (PFOP) and Loan Guaranty(LGY).

VETSNET Release 15 will support the final conversion of records from the legacy system to the new modern payment system for benefits: Burial and Accrued Benefit Payments and continue to support the development of web services for internal and external customers as well as the public at large to provide secure online web interfaces (such as eBenifts.va.gov allowing veterans to apply for benefits online).

Enhancements and ongoing support to VBA's primary application set and single payment engine.  Financial Accounting System (FAS) has no immediate replacement or sunsetting plan, and is currently being expanded in scope to allow for migration of VRE and Education benefits currently paid through BDN.  In addition, FAS requires support to react to the effects of initiatives from various external entities, the Debt Management Center (DMC), the Office of Management and Budget (OMB), the US Department of the Treasury, and ongoing changes implemented by Congress all have items currently in process that will affect payments to our Veterans, and ultimately the FAS engine.   FAS is and will remain for the foreseeable future the payment system for all transformational applications including VBMS and the VRM applications.  Continued FAS development is essential to ensuring that investments in other transformational systems will result in accurate payments to Veterans and Beneficiaries.  Additionally, to ensure proper payments are made to Veterans and Beneficiaries, other VETSNET applications will be necessary until they are sunsetted by their respective replacement VBMS apps. .

The DoD/VA Health Executive Council signed an agreement to utilize the Janus-based graphical user interface (GUI) for an enterprise-level iEHR solution that will be implemented gradually at VA and DoD medical centers throughout the nation. The Performance and Usability Enhancements (PUE) funding stream provides adaptive perfective maintenance and new capabilities for Health Information Exchange (HIE) and Benefits Information Exchange (BIE) between the Department of Veterans Affairs (VA) and the Department of Defense (DoD) multiple applications within the Bidirectional Health Information Exchange (BHIE) system of systems. PUE outcomes include the VLER Data Access Service, (DAS), end-user notification, and two-pass architecture amongst other maintenance and new capability sub-projects on the product users backlog. PUE funds and provides the critical core components of the Virtual Lifetime Electronic Record , (such as the DAS), as well as the present and continuing VA backbone for HIE and BIE between VA and DoD. Clinicians and claims adjudicators rely upon and use, on a daily basis, at a rate of over 5 million queries per year, clinical records that BHIE provides. BHIE provides HIE for clinicians and adjudicators to deliver efficient, effective, and timely treatment and claims processing. Clinicians avoid duplicating radiological, lab, and other tests and studies by using BHIE derived clinical data. If BHIE were not funded, then interagency clinical record exchange would degrade and fail. Patient safety could be seriously and adversely affected, costs could increase, patient satisfaction could decrease, and wounded warriors would not receive timely or effective treatment or claims processing. BHIE provides 31 HIE domains, and the number is anticipated to grow by 107 more.

Objectives / Expected Outcomes: This project implements barcode wireless technology that will enable positive patient identification at the point of care for clinical specimen collection, anatomic pathology specimen collection, and blood administration, as well as reduce adverse events associated with incorrect blood product transfusion; mislabeling of laboratory, anatomical pathology, and blood specimens; and decrease adverse events associated with surgical procedures. BCE supports the Department of Veterans Affairs Strategic Plan FY 2006 2011 Business Performance Measure Objective E.3: Percent of Laboratory specimens that are collected utilizing barcode technology.

Project Name: Compensation and Pension Record Interchange (CAPRI) Tactical Enhancements
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: This project covers the development, modernization, and enhancements (DM&E) of the Compensation and Pension Record Interchange (CAPRI) program. The scope of this effort includes all activities needed to implement enhancements as prioritized by the CAPRI Integrated Product Team (IPT).

This project covers the development, modernization, and enhancements (DM&E) of the Compensation and Pension Record Interchange (CAPRI) program. The scope of this effort includes all activities needed to implement enhancements as prioritized by the CAPRI Integrated Product Team (IPT).
